Three dataframe types — keep them straight.

There are three different things all called a dataframe, and the exam wants you to keep them straight.

The first is the pandas dataframe. It lives entirely in driver memory. Use it for final-mile analysis, for plotting, and for small fixtures.

The second is the pandas-on-Spark dataframe. This one is distributed across the executors. Use it when you want pandas syntax, but at Spark scale.

The third is the Spark dataframe. It is also distributed, and it is the native interface — the best performance, and the most features.

So the key relationship is this. The first one is single-machine. The other two are distributed, over the very same engine. And pandas-on-Spark is simply a Spark dataframe with a pandas-style index added on top. That added index is exactly where the gotchas in the next two sections come from.
